commit_message:
Fix Launch Instance without Cinder

A previous patch altered the defaults in the angular Launch Instance,
but didn't account for those running without Cinder. This patch fixes
those assumptions.

Co-Authored-By: Rob Cresswell <robert.cresswell@outlook.com>
Change-Id: I8dc54fa40fa7eb8ae95a13741405f2a80337b33d
Closes-Bug: 1585761
(cherry picked from commit 723e547e848f580bf5f16899cd2bffa23c77c763)

commit_message:
Related Options

Allows for a list of related options that may be of
interest once option is modified.  This will list
out the related options in generated sample config
files.

Implements: blueprint related-options

Change-Id: I2beedb8d2b046aff0b0a9cd5210c277ce1c6adbc

commit_message:
Only force first letter of fullname to be upper

This change enforce the first and last component
of a fullname to start with an uppercase letter.
This is to keep user's custom capitalisation such as:

* middle name should be lower-case
* keep in-middle uppercase such as "McGinnis"

Change-Id: Ifdad9f05c0d74d18396e9b06bd57c1c0f391be8d

commit_message:
Skip some OSTF tests for upgrade thread

We need to skip tests "Check that required services are running"
and "Instance live migration" for the upgrade test because
the compute node still is marked as compute host in OpenStack
cloud in case of the deletion of this compute host from a cluster

Related-Bug: #1627713

Change-Id: I5db681b0eadf09f1f824b5186c2e4aad87faa059

cloud in case of the deletion of this compute host from a cluster

commit_message:
Add capability to pull in additional quickstart.sh settings

This enables using full-deploy.sh with both downstream CI, as well
as interactive usage for various developer scenarios where one
might wish to pass additional parameters to quickstart.sh

OPT_ADDITIONAL_PARAMETERS will be set to "" only if not defined

Change-Id: I7b697ef289e8b87e10187b158b4b6d2aa4080385

In unittesttools, assertDictEqual() and assertEqual()
are implemented by using '!=' operator. But assertEqual()

"}]
commit_message:
Use assertEqual() instead of assertDictEqual()

In unittesttools, assertDictEqual() and assertEqual()
are implemented by using '!=' operator. But assertEqual()
can handle dict, list, set and so on. So we just call
assertEqual() to make the tests simpler.

Change-Id: I2fdae6892abd3c66bb0702d518101f501e05c4e9

commit_message:
Handle loopback shares without mounting them

Mounting loopback highly available shares is not supported. For
this reason, the previous approach checking whether a share is
local is incorrect.

This patch changes this, attempting to resolve the share address.

Closes-Bug: #1580122
Depends-On: I04ac0b514ccac9c910728da205f0f0f11b43509a
Change-Id: I557c8882dbe45714011d1155dfd553aefafd13e2
(cherry picked from commit c0f5126d62857e3d7258b32e90e3aa0fc5302f84)

* All "qemu-img info" calls are now run under resource limitations
  that limit CPU time to 2 seconds and address space usage to 1 GB.
  This helps avoid any DoS attacks via malicious images.
* All "qemu-img convert" calls now specify the import format so that
  it does not have to be inferred by qemu-img.

SecurityImpact

'}]
commit_message:
Adding constraints around qemu-img calls

* All "qemu-img info" calls are now run under resource limitations
  that limit CPU time to 2 seconds and address space usage to 1 GB.
  This helps avoid any DoS attacks via malicious images.
* All "qemu-img convert" calls now specify the import format so that
  it does not have to be inferred by qemu-img.

SecurityImpact

Change-Id: Ib900bbc05cb9ccd90c6f56ccb4bf2006e30cdc80
Closes-Bug: #1449062
(cherry picked from commit 69a9b659fd48aa3c1f84fc7bc9ae236b6803d31f)

commit_message:
Adding missing localtime mounts and volumes

PS adds missing localtime mount to mariadb,rabbitmq,keystone and
memcached. Also it standardize on host-etc-localtime as volume name
and fixes bunch of other inconsistency encountered with logging
enabled.

Partially-Implemets: blueprint centralized-logging

Change-Id: I849d5a3051d630c236e6babb21c846aef8646350

Final release of octavia for newton (0.9.0)

stable/newton branch.

commit_message:
Fix CentOS Ansible bootstrap

This patch implements the following fixes to the bootstrap-ansible
script in order to make it work successfully on CentOS7:

 - Remove yum check-update as it returns 0 only when no updates are
   available.
 - Add a variable to adjust the virtualenv CLI based on the distro
   used as '--always-copy' does not work on CentOS.


Change-Id: Ia591c3558bd00945dc3076ed19d4c6e364bec939

commit_message:
Make subprocess outputs to text for Python 3

This commit makes subprocess outputs to str with universal_newlines
option. In Python 3, we need to do it explicitly. Otherwise an error
occurs. This commit also adds a unit test to prevent regression.

Change-Id: I2e428a3c57357e47c9057e8dbbbb51ae4b65e4e6

commit_message:
Add 'More Actions...' Actions

This patch adds actions named 'More Actions...' that for each resource type
redirects to the resource's legacy details page.  This is achieved through
a redirect action service that is added just like any other action to the
resource's item action list.

Adds:
* Instances
* Volumes
* Volume Snapshots
* Networks
* Subnets
* Ports
* Routers
* Hypervisors

This change should be able to fix the reported bug. But I would like to
understand why we need specify the preferred disk_format at here. Is
there anything depending on this value beside it must be a valid supported
format? If not, isn't easier for us to just use a common supported 
disk_format which is done in https://review.openstack.org/#/c/366825?
For the zero sized image, the image disk_format seems useless as no real
disk data will be converted from the image. By considering the real disk
data is in the referral volume. Isn't 'raw' a more reasonable option?"}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2016-09-25 15:59:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

@Jianghua, sorry I didn't see you had another patch for this same bug, it wasn't linked into the bug report in launchpad.

I think defaulting to raw for the disk_format would work, but that would still just be a short-term solution since we should use the image schema to determine the disk formats that are available to use in the deployment, because raw might not be in that list.

So I guess the only question is in the preferred order list, and I sorted it this way just because of backward compat for qcow2 being the default in newton."}, {'account_id': 17920, 'date': '2016-09-25 23:52:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

-jay"}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2016-09-26 15:31:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: Code-Review+2

It still feels like we need more understanding of hypervisor standard formats here back to the image server. Because in a multi hypervisor environment like libvirt + hyperv, I feel like this is going to create the wrong answer. Either you give up qcow2 on libvirt, or hyperv snapshots never work.

That being said it wouldn't break any worse than is currently here, and this addresses the xen issue. Leaving for a little bit in case there are other objections."}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2016-09-26 15:44:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

Sean, yeah as you said if you're using multi-hypervisor clouds and you have a backend that doesn't support qcow2, like xen, you're already broken. I think if you're using multiple virt driver backends then you'd have to adjust the image schema to only the common formats that are supported across all backends, like raw."}, {'account_id': 2537, 'date': '2016-09-26 16:17:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2016-09-26 16:58:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: Workflow+1

commit_message:
Determine disk_format for volume-backed snapshot from schema

Xen deployments don't support qcow2 images which is what the
glance v2 API code in nova defaults to, so basically you can't
create a snapshot of a volume-backed instance with glance v2 and
Xen right now.

This change uses the glance v2 image schema to determine the
disk_format to use based on some rules:

1. Look for a preferred disk_format using an ordered list.
2. If we still can't figure it out, just use the first
   supported disk_format available.

Change-Id: Ifaa150fda393e2b49114e30dd5e30e5bf52b4ed1
Closes-Bug: #1616938

commit_message:
RBAC for network sharing

Adds support for the new Newton Neutron RBAC
policy functionality. This allows networks to be
shared across tenants.

For more information, please take a look at:
https://developer.rackspace.com/blog/A-First-Look-at-RBAC-in-the-Liberty-Release-of-Neutron/

Change-Id: Ie433dbd2554648bad7ca9f6940069c85258b03c7
Implements: blueprint neutron-tenant-rbac
(cherry picked from commit aef7fed1409702cf057ee05273f7fe801e5ef4e7)

Return __searchlight-user-role with highlighting

When highlighting is enabled, it is possible to
return the '__searchlight-user-role' field. We
need to stop doing that.

Closes-Bug: #1599332

Swiftclient is logging a 404 when looking for
overcloud-without-mergepy.yaml.  To stop this, disable logging

commit_message:
Stop logging swiftclient errors

Swiftclient is logging a 404 when looking for
overcloud-without-mergepy.yaml.  To stop this, disable logging
below the critical level for swiftclient.  Note that we catch the
resulting exception from swiftclient and log it ourselves if
necessary, so there's no loss of information in the legitimate
error case.

Change-Id: I24144f3ab2b63c4a0f5fc2c9271e4a51a9ea1353
Closes-Bug: 1626267

[{'created': '2016-09-16 18:32:20.000000000', 'message': "Back vNICs with only link-up phys ports by default

Previously, a vNIC's backing devices were chosen purely based on their
saturation (available capacity and number of logical ports), regardless
of link status.  With this change set, the default behavior is NOT to
use physical ports whose link status is 'down'.  This can be changed via
a new config option, [powervm].vnic_check_port_status.  When the default
(True) is overridden (False), the previous behavior is enacted.

Change-Id: I2c9e201243c1134319cc80622e6e9ed7377721ae
"}, {'created': '2016-09-20 19:48:57.000000000', 'message': "Back vNICs with only link-up phys ports

Previously, a vNIC's backing devices were chosen purely based on their
saturation (available capacity and number of logical ports), regardless

Change-Id: I2c9e201243c1134319cc80622e6e9ed7377721ae
"}]
commit_message:
Back vNICs with only link-up phys ports

Previously, a vNIC's backing devices were chosen purely based on their
saturation (available capacity and number of logical ports), regardless
of link status.  With this change set, the behavior is NOT to use
physical ports whose link status is 'down'.

Change-Id: I2c9e201243c1134319cc80622e6e9ed7377721ae

commit_message:
Replace retrying with tenacity

We are replacing all usages of the 'retrying' package with
'tenacity' as the author of retrying is not actively maintaining
the project. Tenacity is a fork of retrying, but has improved the
interface and extensibility (see [1] for more details). Our end
goal here is removing the retrying package from our requirements.

Tenacity provides the same functionality as retrying, but has the
following major differences to account for:
- Tenacity uses seconds rather than ms as retrying did.
- Tenacity has different kwargs for the decorator and
Retrying class itself.
- Tenacity has a different approach for retrying args by
using classes for its stop/wait/retry kwargs.
- By default tenacity raises a RetryError if a retried callable
times out; retrying raises the last exception from the callable.
Tenacity provides backwards compatibility here by offering
the 'reraise' kwarg.
- Tenacity defines 'time.sleep' as a default value for a kwarg.
That said consumers who need to mock patch time.sleep
need to account for this via mocking of time.sleep before
tenacity is imported.
- For retries that check a result, tenacity will raise if the retried
function raises, whereas retrying retried on all exceptions.

This patch updates all usages of retrying with tenacity.
Unit tests will be added where applicable.

Note: This change is not newton critical so projects are welcome
to hold off on committing until post-newton. Ideally this change
will merge by the first part of Ocata so dependant functionality
can land and have time to solidify for Ocata.

[1] https://github.com/jd/tenacity

Change-Id: I18f9a0ab3f73655139c60ee3d059f4859549160f

commit_message:
Do not display Visibility column when All Projects option shown

This patch toggles the visbility column display based on the all-projects
selection, the reason being that the context for the logic used in
determining visibility is changed confusingly, as described in the ticket.

Change-Id: I5140f4f54253d2d274253384434ebdaa43c52e7f
Closes-Bug: 1618210

commit_message:
log info was written to pid file

update the freezer-scheduler config file as follow:
log_file = scheduler.log
log_dir = /home/log

After freezer-scheduler start, the log info was written to pid file.

All open file descriptors were closed while daemonizing. And the pid
file was created and open, The pid file is using the same fileno
as log file. The logger doesn't know its file has already been
closed. So the log info will be written to pid file.

Pass the logging handler through to the daemon using the
DaemonContext's files_preserve option.

Change-Id: I8a0b2da5c2be41a3ae8cedfec44a682ccba353d8
Partial-Bug: #1610904

In two other files there are occurrences of assertTrue(A not in B). Should these be replaced with assertNotIn(A,B)?
File locations:
-trove/tests/unittests/common/test_notification.py: self.assertTrue('users' not in payload)
-trove/tests/unittests/instance/test_instance_models.py: self.assertTrue('10.123.123.123' not in ip)"}, {'account_id': 14576, 'date': '2016-09-20 15:37:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 9664, 'date': '2016-09-20 16:55:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 12732, 'date': '2016-09-21 03:00:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

> (1 comment)

It's more offical."}, {'account_id': 9664, 'date': '2016-09-21 09:03:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: -Code-Review

This is neither a bug, nor a material improvement to the code base. It generates a bunch of churn. Tomorrow someone else will come along and say that "assertTrue( A in B ) is more formal" and we'll go and change this the other way.

I see no strong reason why this change should be merged.

I won't +2 this. On the other hand, I'm not going to -1 this either. I intend to abstain from reviewing this.'}, {'account_id': 16237, 'date': '2016-09-21 09:29:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 14576, 'date': '2016-09-21 15:01:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

> > (1 comment)
 > 
 > It's more offical.

It is always difficult to justify these kind of changes without an official openstack rule/consensus. Feel free to submit a hacking rule to the official openstack repo. See https://review.openstack.org/#/c/283213/"}, {'account_id': 20378, 'date': '2016-09-21 22:17:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

What Petr said. Just like how code changes need unit tests, I believe changes like these should have hacking rules. I've heard counter arguments to this too like, if the hacking project doesn't include these why should we? I think we should lead by example here. I know other projects have their own list of hacking rules we could adopt into our project too. This will stop changes like these."}, {'account_id': 9664, 'date': '2016-09-22 14:00:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

> What Petr said. Just like how code changes need unit tests, I
 > believe changes like these should have hacking rules. I've heard
 > counter arguments to this too like, if the hacking project doesn't
 > include these why should we? I think we should lead by example
 > here. I know other projects have their own list of hacking rules we
 > could adopt into our project too. This will stop changes like
 > these.

I disagree. This change, if it was in shipping code, could have a slightly different merit. This is test code. Implementing hacking rules to use one test method over another seems to imply that someone has way too much time on their hands.

There are real bugs, things that make trove fail, that would benefit from fixing.

If you really have time on your hands, review some code.

It is my stated belief that this change produces code churn for no (none whatsoever) benefit to the project. I will not either +1 or +2 it. But equally, it is not an invalid change (heck, it passes all the tests we have) and so I am also not able to legitimately -1 it.

So, I will just leave it alone. +0"}, {'account_id': 14576, 'date': '2016-09-22 14:57:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

There is a slight difference between the output of the two styles. The assertIn also prints the contents of the variables which may be useful in certain cases.

AssertionError: False is not true
vs.
MismatchError: '1' not in ['3', '4', '5']

I still think that changing files without any kind of rule or check will just generate another very similar patch set sometime later."}, {'account_id': 9664, 'date': '2016-09-23 02:55:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

Use assertIn instead of assertTrue(A in B)

Developers should use assertIn(A, B) instead of assertTrue(A in B ).

TrivialFix

commit_message:
Make neutron-fwaas functional job not experimental

With the advent of additional functional tests, the functional test job
for neutron-fwaas should be moved from the check-experimental queue to
the check queue.  The job is also changed to be voting.

Depends-On: I5c7eab23f3a069721887e6365d563dd9b64805d5

Change-Id: Idef9074f770f545f9e37e3477e56932aeb58748f

commit_message:
Add Grafana dashboard for FWaaS checks

The neutron-fwaas project currently does not have any kind of Grafana
dashboard showing error rates over time, so let's fix that.

Depends-On: I5c7eab23f3a069721887e6365d563dd9b64805d5

commit_message:
Integrate neutron-fwaas with neutron-lib CI

This patch adds the periodic-jobs-with-neutron-lib-master test to
neutron-fwaas.  This will validate that neutron-lib master is working
with the master of neutron-fwaas.

Change-Id: I5c7eab23f3a069721887e6365d563dd9b64805d5

commit_message:
Process OVS trunk bridges associated to VM deletes

If a VM is deleted while the OVS agent is down, upon
restart the OVS trunk bridge is deleted successfully
but the patch ports integration bridge side are left
behind.

This patch makes sure the bridge as well as its peers
are cleaned up.

Closes-bug: #1623708

Change-Id: I3f010755fdb6501753d20357ad2cd0d6c02cf22a

revisions:
[{'created': '2016-07-06 17:31:59.000000000', 'message': 'Add functional regression test for bug 1595962

If the graphical consoles VNC and SPICE are disabled, the live-migration
of an instance will result in an ERROR state. VNC and SPICE are usually
disabled on IBM z systems platforms where graphical consoles are not
available. The serial console is then enabled and VNC + SPICE are
disabled. The logged error message will be:

    "Migration error: Your libvirt version does not support the
    VIR_DOMAIN_XML_MIGRATABLE flag or your destination node does
    not support retrieving listen addresses. In order for live
    migration to work properly you must either disable serial
    console or upgrade your libvirt version."

This functional test executes the live migration flow with enabled serial
console and disabled VNC + SPICE and reproduces bug 1595962.

Change-Id: Ib1b22ce77d8a36e55944acc1fbca042906aa41ef

commit_message:
Add functional regression test for bug 1595962

If the graphical consoles VNC and SPICE are disabled, the live-migration
of an instance will result in an ERROR state. VNC and SPICE are usually
disabled on IBM z systems platforms where graphical consoles are not
available. The serial console is then enabled and VNC + SPICE are
disabled. The logged error message will be:

    "Migration error: Your libvirt version does not support the
    VIR_DOMAIN_XML_MIGRATABLE flag or your destination node does
    not support retrieving listen addresses. In order for live
    migration to work properly you must either disable serial
    console or upgrade your libvirt version."

This functional test executes the live migration flow with enabled serial
console and disabled VNC + SPICE and reproduces bug 1595962.

Related-Bug: 1595962

Change-Id: Ib1b22ce77d8a36e55944acc1fbca042906aa41ef

commit_message:
Determine disk_format for volume-backed snapshot from schema

Xen deployments don't support qcow2 images which is what the
glance v2 API code in nova defaults to, so basically you can't
create a snapshot of a volume-backed instance with glance v2 and
Xen right now.

This change uses the glance v2 image schema to determine the
disk_format to use based on some rules:

1. Look for a preferred disk_format using an ordered list.
2. If we still can't figure it out, just use the first
   supported disk_format available.

Change-Id: Ifaa150fda393e2b49114e30dd5e30e5bf52b4ed1
Closes-Bug: #1616938
(cherry picked from commit 2fe5daeb5fcd2750b0eb083fc5c8bfd3fdb992e2)

commit_message:
Fix NTP servers hieradata

This patch enables correctly setting the NTP server passed via
--ntp-server in the overcloud nodes' /etc/ntp.conf.

Change-Id: Iff644b9da51fb8cd1946ad9d297ba0e94d3d782b

commit_message:
Merge tag '1.1.0' into debian/newton

  * New upstream release.
  * Fixed (build-)depends for this release.
  * Standards-Version is now 3.9.8 (no change).
  * Using OpenStack's Gerrit as VCS URLs.
  * debian/source/options: ignores egg-info and .gitreview.
  * Using pkgos-dh_auto_{test,install} from openstack-pkg-tools >= 52~.
  * Adding bandit, bandit-baseline and bandit-config-generator binary in
    debian/bin to have unit tests and config generation to work.
  * Generate the bandit.yaml using bandit-config-generator.
  * Do not run functional tests that are failing.
  * Do not attempt to install bandit.yaml (file gone upstream).

revisions:
[{'created': '2016-09-09 16:56:45.000000000', 'message': '[WIP] Port password generation from tripleoclient to tripleo-common

At the moment the CLI generates various passwords, this logic is
then not available to the GUI. We should move this to further
standardise the process.

This patch ports the necessary utility methods and adds an action
to generate and store passwords in a mistral environment or retrieve
previously generated passwords from the mistral environment.  The
passwords are stored in parameter_defaults and are used in any
subsequent calls to heat (e.g. Parameters and Stack Creation)

WIP Notes
 - needs tests
 - needs to be added to plan creation or deployment actions
 - ResetParametersAction will destroy these passwords
   - should they be destroyed?
   - add docs to explain what to do after parameters reset to ensure
     passwords exist for deployment
   - add constraint to ResetParametersAction to deny reset if stack
     is running?

Change-Id: Ic476a09f7981d4e6ee12e05b333a18cda5b4626b
'}, {'created': '2016-09-14 15:35:52.000000000', 'message': 'Port password generation from tripleoclient to tripleo-common

At the moment the CLI generates various passwords, this logic is
then not available to the GUI. We should move this to further
standardise the process.

This patch ports the necessary utility methods and adds an action
to generate and store passwords in a mistral environment or retrieve
previously generated passwords from the mistral environment.  The
passwords are stored in parameter_defaults and are used in any
subsequent calls to heat (e.g. Parameters and Stack Creation).
The order of the merge of parameter_defaults and passwords allows
a user to override a password value.

The action is added to workflows in the plan_management workbook.

Closes-Bug: #1621097
Change-Id: Ic476a09f7981d4e6ee12e05b333a18cda5b4626b

commit_message:
Port password generation from tripleoclient to tripleo-common

At the moment the CLI generates various passwords, this logic is
then not available to the GUI. We should move this to further
standardise the process.

This patch ports the necessary utility methods and adds an action
to generate and store passwords in a mistral environment or retrieve
previously generated passwords from the mistral environment.  The action
will generate and replace any missing passwords.  The passwords are
stored in parameter_defaults and are used in any subsequent calls to heat
(e.g. Parameters and Stack Creation).

The order of the merge of parameter_defaults and passwords allows
a user to override a password value.

The action is added to workflows in the plan_management workbook.

Closes-Bug: #1621097
Change-Id: Ic476a09f7981d4e6ee12e05b333a18cda5b4626b

commit_message:
Puppet OpenStack Newton RC2

9.4.0 will be our RC2.

We will need to branch stable/newton for the following modules:
puppet-aodh
puppet-barbican
puppet-ceilometer
puppet-cinder
puppet-designate
puppet-glance
puppet-gnocchi
puppet-heat
puppet-horizon
puppet-ironic
puppet-keystone
puppet-magnum
puppet-manila
puppet-mistral
puppet-murano
puppet-neutron
puppet-nova
puppet-openstack_extras
puppet-openstacklib
puppet-oslo
puppet-ovn
puppet-sahara
puppet-swift
puppet-tempest
puppet-trove
puppet-vswitch
puppet-zaqar

It should be noted that we will not be branching a stable/newton for the
puppet-ceph module.

Change-Id: I68cb99c9c1964c3aa023ea6ab833a447e7e8c750

commit_message:
Increase timeout for pkg_upgrade task

In some slow envs this task can take more then 1800s, so
hence we need to increase timeout.

Change-Id: Icd23b1e95bed91d7312e19cc21010bac1a47f1b8
Closes-bug: #1623093

commit_message:
VCS fix

  * Point the .gitreview file to OpenStack's Gerrit packaging-deb.
  * Using OpenStack's Gerrit as VCS URLs.
  * d/s/options: extend-diff-ignore = "^[.]gitreview$"

Change-Id: Ia1048aa4a58adfac4c7599319e6b651640aa11b3

commit_message:
Update all SHAs for 14.0.0 2016-09-27

This patch updates all the roles to the latest available stable
SHA's, copies the release notes from the updated roles into the
integrated repo, updates all the OpenStack Service SHA's, and
updates the appropriate python requirements pins.

Change-Id: Ib7bf91e0cccc10ebd704ea2a61de83b2d5df0c53

Add the atop service UI settings section

This change adds the appropriate section to UI settings page.
It contains the default settings from the fuel-library and the
note message for an operator.

DocImpact
Change-Id: Ie0e69f58183193455d5d036b45668a3476f1a693

Signed-off-by: Maksim Malchuk <mmalchuk@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Addition of metadata for snapshot in VolumeSnapshot object

When accessing the snapshot object in Horizon codebase, we do not have
access to the metadata of the snapshot. This is because the
VolumeSnapshot object does not have metadata as a member. So added
'metadata' to the VolumeSnapshot object. The fix should provide access
to metadata.
Added test data and test cases for snapshot object with metadata.

Closes-Bug: 1542468

Change-Id: I4ae2e7a74d3ddbff8493b42f8f86c7002229cf8c

commit_message:
Always pass info to external DNS

The current logic prior to this patch would _only_ set pass info to
external DNS under the following circumstances:

* The network is a flat non-provider network
* The network has 2 or more subnets

These are strange requirements to say the least, but I see no reason
not to be setting DNS for every instance spawn, regardless of network
type.

Change-Id: I6204a6a5b513b4b8b00ca457c1bdcb8db1fc4b97
Closes-Bug: 1616274

commit_message:
Add atop configuration settings

Now the atop setting are configurable from UI and can be overriden in
hiera. Also, this change adds idempotency and fix noop tests.

DocImpact
Depends-On: Ie0e69f58183193455d5d036b45668a3476f1a693
Change-Id: I59cea9ea5ca31c20db2cf3eaaebe09bad0abdcf8
Closes-Bug: #1597250
Signed-off-by: Maksim Malchuk <mmalchuk@mirantis.com>
(cherry picked from commit a7f03d7c55446dd035b499046b6ffc86ec112bed)
(cherry picked from commit a55cbdb8c812a3d1c4fd5be3a42d11b0e26809b9)

[{'created': '2016-09-23 14:15:20.000000000', 'message': "Fix metadata removal

This fixes the case where known metadata types were not being removed
upon saving.  When trying to apply name changes to the provided value,
the work was done out of order, causing the item to be taken out
of the 'removed' list.

Change-Id: I0058ce369a9616b4c49f3d6d1a54cf69144e2f0c
Co-Authored-By: Matt Wood <matt.wood@hpe.com>

"}]
commit_message:
Fix metadata removal

This fixes the case where known metadata types were not being removed
upon saving.  When trying to apply name changes to the provided value,
the work was done out of order, causing the item to be taken out
of the 'removed' list.

Change-Id: I0058ce369a9616b4c49f3d6d1a54cf69144e2f0c
Co-Authored-By: Matt Wood <matt.wood@hpe.com>
Closes-Bug: 1618578
(cherry picked from commit 2425e6e860932514c963844dfab6d24b023883bf)

commit_message:
Add quotes to versions

If developer try to specify verions using `>=` without quotes,
yaml loader exception will be raised during uploding package
to murano.

Closes-Bug: #1627983
Change-Id: I42fad7ae6c4e2aff191ca165a364facbeb027845

messages:
[{'account_id': 23633, 'date': '2016-09-27 15:49:45.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 23633, 'date': '2016-09-27 16:03:16.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

revisions:
[{'created': '2016-09-27 15:49:45.000000000', 'message': 'Prevent attempts to "filter" find() calls by globally unique IDs

This use case isn't covered by our current APIs:

  GET /entities?id={entity_id}
  GET /entities?entity_id={entity_id}

Because we have a dedicated API for that:

  GET /entities/{entity_id}

But our find() methods generally support **kwargs, which are passed as
query parameters to keystone. When an 'id' or 'entity_id' is passed to
keystone as a query parameter, keystone rightly ignores it and returns
an unfiltered collection.

This change raises a client-side TypeError (as you'd expect when you try
to pass a keyword argument that a function isn't expecting), and
includes a helpful suggestion to try calling get() instead.

Change-Id: Ieb44b3ada360a2691b95528c80780249a3906627
Closes-Bug: #1626640
'}]
commit_message:
Prevent attempts to "filter" find() calls by globally unique IDs

This use case isn't covered by our current APIs:

  GET /entities?id={entity_id}
  GET /entities?entity_id={entity_id}

Because we have a dedicated API for that:

  GET /entities/{entity_id}

But our find() methods generally support **kwargs, which are passed as
query parameters to keystone. When an 'id' or 'entity_id' is passed to
keystone as a query parameter, keystone rightly ignores it and returns
an unfiltered collection.

This change raises a client-side TypeError (as you'd expect when you try
to pass a keyword argument that a function isn't expecting), and
includes a helpful suggestion to try calling get() instead.

Change-Id: Ieb44b3ada360a2691b95528c80780249a3906627

commit_message:
Add Apache 2.0 license to source file

As per OpenStack licensing guide lines [1]:
[H102 H103] Newly contributed Source Code should be licensed under
the Apache 2.0 license.
[H104] Files with no code shouldnt contain any license header nor
comments, and must be left completely empty.

[1] http://docs.openstack.org/developer/hacking/#openstack-licensing

Change-Id: If6676d7bf7409ebec2a035bdae158b644e19a861

commit_message:
Reload only components tab of environment page

Previously during the deployment of env  without services all tabs
of env were reloading. Now only components page reloads.

Change-Id: I60780940a1ff8b936f323e71bab5f4adb3308247
Closes-bug: #1607692

revisions:
[{'created': '2016-09-23 14:39:33.000000000', 'message': 'Fix for vtep port Ovn Nb database requires vtep port options to be specified as follows. The code sets the vtep keys wrongly. As a result, vtep-gw cannot bind to the vtep port. The port binding profile keys are also changed to be consistent with OVN NB vtep keys.

These options apply when is vtep.

Required. The name of the VTEP gateway. Required. A logical switch name connected by the VTEP gateway. Closes-Bug: 1624161 Change-Id: Iff51c5b2edaf0b2e5c80fafe012ec6feb495f7f3 (cherry picked from commit 275475fc9ff8539d952ec1e3bc0e2aa61b262c74) '}]
commit_message:
Fix for vtep port Ovn Nb database requires vtep port options to be specified as follows. The code sets the vtep keys wrongly. As a result, vtep-gw cannot bind to the vtep port. The port binding profile keys are also changed to be consistent with OVN NB vtep keys.

These options apply when is vtep.

Required. The name of the VTEP gateway. Required. A logical switch name connected by the VTEP gateway. Closes-Bug: 1624161 Change-Id: Iff51c5b2edaf0b2e5c80fafe012ec6feb495f7f3 (cherry picked from commit 275475fc9ff8539d952ec1e3bc0e2aa61b262c74)

commit_message:
Allow 200 as a response from /v2/zone/recordsets

Designate can return a 200 or a 202, depending on the status
of an API call.

This allows tempest to accept the 200

Change-Id: I0e9c38bb8f11f7c9ee31d4f7eb710b7df30674df

commit_message:
Reset rabbitmq default for net_ticktime to 60 sec

This parameter should be increased to eliminate the triggering partition
handling logic on spurious network partitions/outages.

Closes-Bug: #1598154
Change-Id: I1759ee27ddeae9334d7d9653d87127a914b79a37
(backported 7f7214abf3e174e9ef84dc86fae2f5b2ca4a237d)

(1 comment)

I know you are still in progress.  let me ask a very naive question:

 * What is the cardinality from policy to network? 1:1, 1:*, *:*?'}, {'account_id': 10063, 'date': '2016-07-29 19:08:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Each policy rule is its own entity - essentially id -> (tenant, target_type, target_id)

I've always been somewhat opposed to setting up additional data storage because it will inevitably add complexity; the alternatives in this case are changing the notifications or storing the policy id with the tenant_id in each Network (or subnet or port or whatever else). One obvious concern - when we reindex, we'll need to scrub that extra state."}, {'account_id': 7665, 'date': '2016-07-29 19:13:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

thanks, steve but still wondering if a policy only exists in relationship to a single network or not or if mulitple networks can reference the same policy.'}, {'account_id': 10063, 'date': '2016-07-29 19:19:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

One policy rule, one network (or more specifically one object), one tenant. To allow tenant abc to two networks would require two rule instances and i think they're immutable."}, {'account_id': 14680, 'date': '2016-08-02 00:02:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Hi Travis,

Just to add some more details. An RBAC policy is a 1:1 mapping between a network and a tenant. The policy refers to an RBAC object, which is just a network ID. Since we just care about sharing a network, I'll ignore the type (network) and action (access_as_shared) for the policy.

To create an RBAC policy, we would do the following:

    neutron rbac-create <Tenant1 ID> <Network1 ID>

This will share the network with Network1 ID to the tenant with Tenant1 ID. If another network is to be shared with the same tenant, this will require another RBAC policy to be created:

    neutron rbac-create <Tenant1 ID> <Network2 ID>

If the same network is to be shared with a different tenant, this will also require another RBAC policy to be created:

    neutron rbac-create <Tenant2 ID> <Network1 ID>

Each of these commands will create a different RBAC policy with a different ID.

Here is a blog post with more information:

https://developer.rackspace.com/blog/A-First-Look-at-RBAC-in-the-Liberty-Release-of-Neutron/"}, {'account_id': 14680, 'date': '2016-08-04 01:43:26.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 14680, 'date': '2016-08-04 01:44:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Workflow-1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2016-08-04 01:59:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

commit_message:
RBAC for network sharing

Adds support for the new Newton Neutron RBAC
policy functionality. This allows networks to be
shared across tenants.

For more information, please take a look at:
https://developer.rackspace.com/blog/A-First-Look-at-RBAC-in-the-Liberty-Release-of-Neutron/

Change-Id: Ie433dbd2554648bad7ca9f6940069c85258b03c7
Implements: blueprint neutron-tenant-rbac

commit_message:
Add X-Frame-Options header to Nginx

This commit adds the 'X-Frame-Options: SAMEORIGIN' header by default
to all HTTP responses to instruct the modern browsers to prevent from
clickjacking attacks.

Change-Id: I6fb9fa81c454cf93e3c386026588b345da760c73
Closes-Bug: #1592794
Signed-off-by: Maksim Malchuk <mmalchuk@mirantis.com>

[{'created': '2016-03-30 11:26:28.000000000', 'message': "Hardcode part_power for swift ring builder

The default part_power for 3 controllers should
be 10. Previous deployments calculated the part_power
of 3 controllers to 10, so this should be preserved
for future deployments.

For custom deployments which require a different part_power,
it should be set in swift_hash in the key 'ring_part_power'.

DocImpact: Should advise users before upgrading from a prior
release about swift ring part_power.
Change-Id: Ic7f8f6824712cc2bb5b530fe1300c9a3ac4ce302
Closes-Bug: #1498368
(cherry picked from commit 22e51270d56a650fdb3b76549e07cf93be31bb4b)
"}]
commit_message:
Hardcode part_power for swift ring builder

The default part_power for 3 controllers should
be 10. Previous deployments calculated the part_power
of 3 controllers to 10, so this should be preserved
for future deployments.

For custom deployments which require a different part_power,
it should be set in swift_hash in the key 'ring_part_power'.

DocImpact: Should advise users before upgrading from a prior
release about swift ring part_power.
Change-Id: Ic7f8f6824712cc2bb5b530fe1300c9a3ac4ce302
Closes-Bug: #1498368
(cherry picked from commit 22e51270d56a650fdb3b76549e07cf93be31bb4b)

commit_message:
tox: shorter envdir name for upgrade target

The shebang of a script in linux is limited to 127 chars (execve
limitation). In gate, within the virtualenv the python path in all
binaries shebang is a bit long:

/home/jenkins/workspace/gate-gnocchi-tox-db-py35-postgresql-file-upgrade-from-2.2-ubuntu-xenial/.tox/py35-postgresql-file-upgrade-from-2.2/bin/python

This change sets a envdir manually to workaround the issue and keep
explicit name in tox target.

Change-Id: I6edadc5e03891595db23afc12ee36a519989bd8a

Add the atop service UI settings section

This change adds the appropriate section to UI settings page.
It contains the default settings from the fuel-library and the
note message for an operator.

DocImpact
Change-Id: Ie0e69f58183193455d5d036b45668a3476f1a693

Signed-off-by: Maksim Malchuk <mmalchuk@mirantis.com>

I'm a bit concerned in just making this change to get past testing, where are the release notes associated with the fact that we need a shared lock space? And if so, it feels like we need to revisit this fact with oslo.concurrency and not make users provide the right lock path themselves or get breakage."}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2016-08-09 00:38:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

It starts to feel that at some point lock files aren't the best approach for what is being done here but instead an actual lock manager (one say that tooz supports) is better suited for this...

If we start to have a hierarchy of locks in certain directories that projects are aware of the meaning of, that gets into some interesting territory and I feel that oslo.concurrency or even tooz at that point isn't the right place for that (because the meaning of what that hierachy and namespacing is will need to be some kind of API between projects and tooz and oslo.concurrency only provide the primitives that could be used to create such an API but they don't provide the API themselves)."}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2016-08-09 00:40:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Perhaps we want to start a email on openstack-dev, because at a point this gets into the larger question of what is that API, how does it work, what is the right description of that API...

I can theorize how it would look or what it would be, but that's probably going to require larger assumptions and agreement before we even get that far."}, {'account_id': 12924, 'date': '2016-08-09 23:23:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Sorry for the delayed response, I'm actively wanting to push this stuff but am traveling at the moment. So, I can appreciate some good old fashion bike shedding about locking as much as the next dev... but I do think we could maybe take a multi-pronged approach to tackle this.


A couple of points I think are important to keep in mind for this:

* Its only really an issue if c-vol and n-cpu are on the same node, this doesn't seem super common in "real" deployments  (hence why no one seemed to notice this as an issue in all the years it has been working this way...)

* Even if we change the way the locking works, it will take time and more than likely will not make it into N. We'll be testing and using DevStack with this code for a while :(


What I would propose is that we go ahead with this bandaid in DevStack, and make sure that we raise up the issue to Cinder, Nova, and the Doc writers so that its can be correctly documented somewhere. In parallel to this we can start a discussion on a longer term solution for this that we can all agree on and get community support for.


Does that sound reasonable?'}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2016-08-10 00:02:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Seems ok to me.'}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2016-08-10 00:06:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Though I would say this isn't exactly bike-shedding but more of fundamental API(s) between projects that need to be fixed but ya, fair nuff :-P"}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2016-08-12 01:08:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-2

not wanting to put a work around in devstack to corruption by default behavior in cinder/nova is not bikeshedding.

I also think this is something that the cinder/nova teams are probably not fully aware is an issue.

So, please start with landing the release note in both of those projects so it's clear that the core teams on both understand what's being asked of operators here to not corrupt their data by default, with no warning.

After the release notes are in, this is game to land in devstack."}, {'account_id': 12924, 'date': '2016-08-12 04:13:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

As requested:

https://review.openstack.org/354501

https://review.openstack.org/354502


As an aside, I kinda disagree with the tactic of holding a bug fix hostage like this... IMO (heavy emphasis on the "my opinion"), this change needs to happen either way, so blocking it just kind of.. what? Encouragement? Luckily as an active community member and (still IMO) a pretty reasonable human I'm game for documenting broken stuff, but had I fucked off and not followed through we would still just have a broken config in Devstack. What good is that?

I'll admit my comment earlier on bike-shedding was a tad uncalled for, so I apologize if it sounded like I was dismissing the need to fix the underlying issue as unworthy of pursuit. What I meant (mostly as a joke) was that a thread on openstack-dev to delve into "the larger question of what is that API, how does it work, what is the right description of that API." would surely not be quick, on topic, or be solving the volume attachment problems of current nova and cinder needing this config option set. Again though, thats just like, my opinion.'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2016-08-14 01:41:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I came to the same conclusion today when reviewing the release note change proposed to nova. I think we need:

1. This change so we actually CI with what we're telling people to do in release notes.

2. An update to the lock_path help text in the config option since that's going to have a better chance of being read than release notes just for newton in cinder and nova - new people after newton won't see that.

But I'm +1 on this to move forward for now."}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2016-08-14 01:41:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2016-09-27 15:20:21.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

This is really not a deployment feasable direction.'}]

commit_message:
Use a shared lock directory for Nova and Cinder

When running nova and cinder on the same node they require
synchronization for locks in os-brick. To support this
os-brick uses named locks, but it requires the two to use
the same directories for their locks.

Change-Id: Ic76b90be08bf03a9dfa3d3916fba4603594cac8f

commit_message:
Filter data when deserializing RevokeEvents

The RevokeEvent loads in with **data meaning that the data is
passed to the RevokeEvent.__init__ method without any sanitization.

We now filter and report explicitly where we had the issue. If the
key is not relevant to the RevokeEvent it is ignored (and logged
via debug).

This bug should be effectively resolved but maintained open for
tracking purposes until we are comfortable in simply closing it
out.

Change-Id: Ife604ae30224581760042932b8561ab7961e993b
Partial-Bug: #1609566

commit_message:
Refetch subnet/network from DB in ML2 update ops

This ensures that any extensions run in the ML2 extension framework
that bump the revision number of the subnet or network result in the
altered revision number being returned to the API caller and passed
into the ML2 mech drivers and callback handlers.

Closes-Bug: #1627628
Change-Id: Ieb37a3833ee52c671419c6dc981cf91c2366ae94

[{'created': '2016-07-22 01:17:22.000000000', 'message': 'Unable to add classless-static-route in extra_dhcp_opt extension

When adding classless-static-route in extra_dhcp_opt for a port,
neutron client complains syntax error. The reason is neutron client
interprets the "," inside the opt_value as a delimiter of key-value
pairs for --extra-dhcp-opt.

This patch allows users to use spaces in the opt_value.
Then convert spaces to commas when writing them to opts file.

This is one of two proposed solutions described in #1605421.

Closes-Bug: #1605421
Change-Id: I5bc3446d47ff417143038a437c7e7a5c8fe140c4
'}]
commit_message:
Unable to add classless-static-route in extra_dhcp_opt extension

When adding classless-static-route in extra_dhcp_opt for a port,
neutron client complains syntax error. The reason is neutron client
interprets the "," inside the opt_value as a delimiter of key-value
pairs for --extra-dhcp-opt.

This patch allows users to use spaces in the opt_value.
Then convert spaces to commas when writing them to opts file.

This is one of two proposed solutions described in #1605421.

Closes-Bug: #1605421
Change-Id: I5bc3446d47ff417143038a437c7e7a5c8fe140c4

commit_message:
Add Ironic vars and play to central test repo

Ironic requires some new glance vars, as well as the ironic vars.

This ensures facts are set for the ironic host, as well as adding the
test-install-ironic.yml play so it can benefit from the common tasks
more easily.

Change-Id: Ib5dee3ee50a4a1a443ebf7b744001d6f5bd40d1e

commit_message:
standardize release note page ordering

In order to support automatically updating the release notes when we
create stable branches, we want the pages to be in a standard order.
This patch updates the order to be reverse chronological, so the most
recent notes appear at the top.

Change-Id: I8d7bc165dd1c623498397ac9259f767b3d371172

commit_message:
Modify the general API for the database backend

Currently database connection is ahead of loading opts
from config file, which leading to config opts can't
take effect on database selection.

Closes-bug: #1627568

Change-Id: Ibbc20231c146216961d329503c245f2d4cd534b4
Signed-off-by: Kevin Zhao <kevin.zhao@linaro.org>

commit_message:
Remove default=None when set value in Config

By default oslo.cfg sets the default values as None [1], There is no need
to explicitly do this.

[1] https://github.com/openstack/oslo.config/blob/master/oslo_config/cfg.py#L829

Change-Id: I072f88b8c5277cffa155c1b517cf9a4411dadc41

commit_message:
Misc fixes

This PS fixes some formatting issues with minikube.rst. Changes a
few defaults to make things more consistent and orders the nodeport
config options together. Adds a way to expose the rabbitmq
management service externally if desired. It fixes setting the
external ip address for all in one setups that need an ip set.

Change-Id: I7756ebe6509a2e5c4c475ce7076bd56ffd7ef5ef

commit_message:
Use centos-release-ceph-jewel package

Previously we had to download from github the testing .repo file
to enable the testing repo for Ceph/Jewel. Now the Ceph packages
moved out of the testing phase and we can install the 'release'
package.

Change-Id: I24460a00e516a289b1fe5f8948f586ebe3de2505
Depends-On: I14003a8f00a4f07bcddafe6dc5928126f22362bd

commit_message:
tox: Install like other OpenStack projects

We had tools/tox_install.sh for the case we could depend on neutron
which was not on pypi. In the end, we depend only on
python-neutronclient and as such, this workaround is not necessary and
only makes tox slower.

Change-Id: I558c1dbb2730ef41d3ec7d211f6079f051b53b6d
Signed-off-by: Antoni Segura Puimedon <antonisp@celebdor.com>

I'm still worried about convert.py.  With no -f option, qemu-img attempts to infer the image format, which I imagine would mean doing something like whatever it does to process the qemu-img info call.  Looks like there are a few things we could do here:

(1) make a qemu-img info call with the proc restrictions, and if it fails, don't attempt the conversion

(2) add a config option to allow the proc limits to be specified, with some kind of reasonable default (though I have no idea what that default would be)

(3) do nothing, just emphasize in the release note that tasks (particularly the conversion and introspection tasks) should only be exposed to trusted users

Thoughts?"}, {'account_id': 8158, 'date': '2016-09-23 19:24:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

> I'm still worried about convert.py.  With no -f option, qemu-img
 > attempts to infer the image format, which I imagine would mean
 > doing something like whatever it does to process the qemu-img info
 > call.  Looks like there are a few things we could do here:
 > 
 > (1) make a qemu-img info call with the proc restrictions, and if it
 > fails, don't attempt the conversion

If the method is crafted out to a common place and we handle the right exceptions or add more if..then..else clauses, we will avoid such slips.

 > 
 > (2) add a config option to allow the proc limits to be specified,
 > with some kind of reasonable default (though I have no idea what
 > that default would be)

We've agreed to be conservative about adding configs especially for tasks. I think if operator want some different setup they are welcome to add more or different flows to this default setup.

 > 
 > (3) do nothing, just emphasize in the release note that tasks
 > (particularly the conversion and introspection tasks) should only
 > be exposed to trusted users

This can be an option as the tasks api is admin only by default and glance team wants to advertise so. (right?)

If this introduces too much refactoring it might not qualify and we might be stranding folks on stable branches."}, {'account_id': 5314, 'date': '2016-09-23 21:33:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Answering Nikhil's points out-of-order:

> We've agreed to be conservative about adding configs especially for tasks. I think if operator want some different setup they are welcome to add more or different flows to this default setup.

Good point, let's not add any options now.

> > do nothing just emphasize in the release note that tasks should only be exposed to trusted users
> This can be an option as the tasks api is admin only by default and glance team wants to advertise so. (right?)

I agree, and think it's the way to go.  Plus, it is consistent with our position over the past few cycles.

> If the method is crafted out to a common place and we handle the right exceptions or add more if..then..else clauses, we will avoid such slips.

I'm thinking we'll need to refactor the tasks workflow in Pike (possibly in Ocata, depending on how import develops).  I think we need a "sanitize" step in the flow that's completely independent of the other tasks, and any flow that handles end-user-supplied data, first pumps it through the "sanitize" task.  Then the downstream tasks won't have to worry about this kind of thing (hopefully).  We can figure out the best way to do this on the Pike spec.

So I agree with Ian here that let's not refactor too much at the moment so this fix can be easily backported.'}, {'account_id': 2537, 'date': '2016-09-23 22:38:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

 > moment so this fix can be easily backported.'}, {'account_id': 12000, 'date': '2016-09-26 13:28:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

As Daniel points out on the bug [1], Brian is correct that we need -f to be provided otherwise these qemu-img commands *will* try to guess the format and that will be a problem.

I'm also unconvinced we can refactor the exception handling and command usage into one place like Nikhil wants after looking more closely at the usage in both places.

One exception block checks the errno value which Flavio wrote to handle a missing executable (I assume qemu-img) while the other just logs the message and reraises it for any exception.

What we could do, is safely take the bit that looks like

    putils.trycmd('qemu-img', 'info', ...)

Into a separate function and work on refactoring the error handling in Ocata in a follow-on patch if we *really* want it to be that concise in these places.

This will mean that we'll have an qemu-img-info command that does the correct thing (uses -f) and takes the parameters necessary to work. Let's also start with the most minimal definition of that common method. We can put it in glance.async.utils if everyone agrees.

[1]: https://bugs.launchpad.net/glance/+bug/1449062/comments/73"}, {'account_id': 8158, 'date': '2016-09-26 14:50:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
Adding constraints around qemu-img calls

* All "qemu-img info" calls are now run under resource limitations
  that limit CPU time to 2 seconds and address space usage to 1 GB.
  This helps avoid any DoS attacks via malicious images.
* All "qemu-img convert" calls now specify the import format so that
  it does not have to be inferred by qemu-img.

SecurityImpact

Change-Id: Ib900bbc05cb9ccd90c6f56ccb4bf2006e30cdc80
Closes-Bug: #1449062

commit_message:
Add is_authenticated and is_anonymous properties

See
https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/1.10/releases/1.10/#using-user-is-authenticated-and-user-is-anonymous-as-methods

is_anonymous() and is_authenticated() functions are now properties, and
throw critical security warnings when using python manage.py check in
django 1.10

The duplication is just to make it explicit which code paths are being
followed. They could be refactored to remove it, but in a few months
when we move to the next LTS we would just end up removing the refactors
since there would once again be a single path.

We also removed the `margin` parameter, since it is never used anywhere.
This will be documented in a Horizon release note.

Change-Id: I7a92089ae62a9017274002648f26f13bc34709d9
(cherry picked from commit 00346889c99c26f1bbdaf3c392bac6dfefb509c7)

[{'created': '2016-07-17 15:16:09.000000000', 'message': 'Keepalived global_defs configuration entries required to avoid DNS lookup

This changeset addresses a particular L3-HA Neutron deployment scenario
in which the DNS server configured for the management network is not
also accessible from the virtual router namespace (i.e. over the
external network).
Keepalived uses the hostname against getaddrinfo twice to set default
values for the router_id and notification_email_from global configuration
attributes. If the hostname cannot be resolved through /etc/hosts and
if the nameserver is not reachable, long delays are incurred during
keepalived startup and configuration reload, causing VRRP state flapping
and dropped traffic over floating IPs.

Setting router_id and notification_email_from in the keepalived
configuration avoids unnecessary DNS lookups. However, this solution
is only effective with keepalived >= 1.2.17. Older versions still
exhibit the same problem with or without this patch.

Closes-Bug: #1511722
Change-Id: If6e31d164bd6ade52997bc0073ef50cdbc99ec93

commit_message:
Keepalived global_defs configuration entries required to avoid DNS lookup

This changeset addresses a particular L3-HA Neutron deployment scenario
in which the DNS server configured for the management network is not
also accessible from the virtual router namespace (i.e. over the
external network).
Keepalived uses the hostname against getaddrinfo twice to set default
values for the router_id and notification_email_from global configuration
attributes. If the hostname cannot be resolved through /etc/hosts and
if the nameserver is not reachable, long delays are incurred during
keepalived startup and configuration reload, causing VRRP state flapping
and dropped traffic over floating IPs.

Setting router_id and notification_email_from in the keepalived
configuration avoids unnecessary DNS lookups. However, this solution
is only effective with keepalived >= 1.2.17. Older versions still
exhibit the same problem with or without this patch.

Closes-Bug: #1511722
Change-Id: If6e31d164bd6ade52997bc0073ef50cdbc99ec93

[{'created': '2016-09-26 21:30:02.000000000', 'message': "WIP Adding logging to kolla-kubernetes services

This PS adds sidecar logging container to kolla-kubernetes services.
Since different OpenStack components can generate logs in different
formats, logging config map has a variable 'log_format' identifying
required format.
At this moment types included are:
'openstack' - which covers most openstack services
'mariadb' - mariadb logs
'keystone' - apache2 type of logs
In case log_format variable is not defined, format 'none' will be used.

Change-Id: I0aecf158453029f8266b62352f0e93f00329eb80
Partially-Implements: blueprint centralized-logging

commit_message:
Adding logging to kolla-kubernetes services

This PS adds sidecar logging container to kolla-kubernetes services.
Since different OpenStack components can generate logs in different
formats, logging config map has a variable 'log_format' identifying
required format.
At this moment types included are:
'openstack' - which covers most openstack services
'mariadb' - mariadb logs
'keystone' - apache2 type of logs
'horizon' - apache2 type of logs
'rabbitmq' - json type of log
In case log_format variable is not defined, format 'none' will be used.

Change-Id: I0aecf158453029f8266b62352f0e93f00329eb80
Partially-Implements: blueprint centralized-logging

[{'created': '2016-08-10 09:41:05.000000000', 'message': 'Add is_authenticated and is_anonymous properties

See
https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/1.10/releases/1.10/#using-user-is-authenticated-and-user-is-anonymous-as-methods

is_anonymous() and is_authenticated() functions are now properties, and

commit_message:
Add is_authenticated and is_anonymous properties

See
https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/1.10/releases/1.10/#using-user-is-authenticated-and-user-is-anonymous-as-methods

is_anonymous() and is_authenticated() functions are now properties, and
throw critical security warnings when using python manage.py check in
django 1.10

The duplication is just to make it explicit which code paths are being
followed. They could be refactored to remove it, but in a few months
when we move to the next LTS we would just end up removing the refactors
since there would once again be a single path.

We also removed the `margin` parameter, since it is never used anywhere.
This will be documented in a Horizon release note.

Change-Id: I7a92089ae62a9017274002648f26f13bc34709d9

commit_message:
Type min_part_hours,part_power,repl_number as int

This PR ensures that if a string is entered as the var it will be forced
to an "int" type, which is expected by the script.

Change-Id: I8d7f3c4894c2b0975893ebb30b734ae7fccfbc22

[{'created': '2016-09-26 07:16:29.000000000', 'message': 'Add flag assignment before possible referenced

"name 'flag' is not defined" exception may be reported at
L169 self.assertTrue(flag) in the following assuming circumstance:
flavor was created successfully, retrieved okay, but not found in
flavors list.

The solution is adding flag init defination 'False' like other
tests in this file.

Change-Id: I63a4b029dff2131336f7bc93f2699a4ae4ca6519
'}]
commit_message:
Add flag assignment before possible referenced

"name 'flag' is not defined" exception may be reported at
L169 self.assertTrue(flag) in the following assuming circumstance:
flavor was created successfully, retrieved okay, but not found in
flavors list.

The solution is adding flag init defination 'False' like other
tests in this file.

Change-Id: I63a4b029dff2131336f7bc93f2699a4ae4ca6519

commit_message:
Changed docker_restart_policy to unless-stopped

Current implementation has docker_restart_policy "always" and
docker_restart_policy_retry:"10" which should be mutually exclusive.
"unless-stopped" will restart the containers on any exit state
but not start on daemon startup if container was put to stopped state before.
Closes-Bug: #1621187

Change-Id: I4d881cd123a55625121b7a9047385e9b54e2e129

The | bool was forcing the second var to be a "bool" meaning the
statement always evaluated to true.

This fixes the issue and ensures that when the addresses are the same
the "swift_dedicated_replication" setting evaluates to "False", and when
they are different it evaluates to "True".

Change-Id: Ic0aedbd1a5a5faafd0a1191b50ade90d46503057
'}]
commit_message:
Fix bool evaluation for dedicated repl network

The | bool was forcing the second var to be a "bool" meaning the
statement always evaluated to true.

This fixes the issue and ensures that when the addresses are the same
the "swift_dedicated_replication" setting evaluates to "False", and when
they are different it evaluates to "True".

Change-Id: Ic0aedbd1a5a5faafd0a1191b50ade90d46503057

commit_message:
Add rolename setting for tempest

Allow tempest to deploy itself, using the tempest_rolename variable,
this is required for tempest to use the test-install-tempest.yml play,
as the rolename will be "{toxinidir}" for the tempest repository.

Change-Id: I4834413b4a006567be4bcc649bd674dcb3c93c2e

[{'created': '2016-09-21 11:41:15.000000000', 'message': 'Ensure ring always rebalances.

As this is for testing only, we should set the
"swift_pretend_min_part_hours_passed" variable to True. This will ensure
the ring is rebalanced and that we don't have to wait for an hour to
pass before any ring changes can be made.

This is especially important for MR swift where the ring will refuse to
rebalance on the second region's introduction, as min_part_hours has
not passed yet.

Change-Id: Ide83c1570e69e8fa2b0803e49215ef24d1fd2484
'}]
commit_message:
Ensure ring always rebalances.

As this is for testing only, we should set the
"swift_pretend_min_part_hours_passed" variable to True. This will ensure
the ring is rebalanced and that we don't have to wait for an hour to
pass before any ring changes can be made.

This is especially important for MR swift where the ring will refuse to
rebalance on the second region's introduction, as min_part_hours has
not passed yet.

Change-Id: Ide83c1570e69e8fa2b0803e49215ef24d1fd2484

commit_message:
Add ExportPortFailure exception

When creating security group rule failed, kuryr-libnetwork raise
an exception:
'module' object has no attribute 'ExportPortFailure'.
Meanwhile ExportPortFailure is missing in the imported module.

This patch add missing ExportPortFailure in kuryr-lib.

Change-Id: Ia5cbe785d3bdecf0981438aa850d9d9da3ab38c8
Closes-Bug: #1627911

commit_message:
Limit cookie usage to download routes

In order to fix CSRF issues we gradually getting rid of cookies. The
first step is to limit their usage to download routes only.

Change-Id: I0ec451e8a536dc37af08f2cd2efe58500737b56e
Closes-Bug: #1592732
(cherry picked from commit cb8d2d53f5c90efa1fc66eaa3e85b1fdf32d4226)

Since the ceilometer-api binary was generated by pbr, its startup
parameters are different from previous. The difference must be
applied to devstack plugin script or ceilometer-api cant start
after devstack has run if the "enable_httpd_mod_wsgi_services" is

'}]
commit_message:
Modify startup parameters of ceilometer-api in devstack script

Since the ceilometer-api binary was generated by pbr, its startup
parameters are different from previous. The difference must be
applied to devstack plugin script or ceilometer-api cant start
after devstack has run if the "enable_httpd_mod_wsgi_services" is
set to false in local.conf.

Change-Id: Ie1aa11cc167251ca750041b3333e1c9c31227ad1
Closes-Bug: #1626531

commit_message:
Enable tlsproxy on "core" tempest jobs

This enables tlsproxy on our "core" tempest jobs. This will prevent
regressions in devstack itself, the projects, and their clients. Note we
don't just enable this by default in devstack because many things don't
work quite right with TLS yet, but the core things do.

Depends-On: Ic21c0213c8ea91f3d7c30f03227af7b5a107b527
Depends-On: I37d247b68911dc85f55adec6a7952ed321c1b1d8
Change-Id: I4885c748c8ab2c6e0cd37cc3e1f1efc447fecdb3

commit_message:
Use --config-file from oslo instead of --config

Switch freezer-agent to oslo config file parsing.

--config is breaking the typing of int values.
Oslo.config is smarter about typing.

Change-Id: Id4ddf61fbb3adfb11e6a3c047a15284dcf16f0c0

commit_message:
Work around Ansible vcpu fact bug on ppc64le

This changes how ceilometer_wsgi_processes is set to work around a
bug in Ansible where ansible_processor_vcpus is reported as 0 on
ppc64le today due to issues with /proc/cpuinfo format differences.
An upstream fix has been proposed at [1].

[1] - ansible/ansible#16533

commit_message:
Remove unused methods

Manila doesn't use methods ensure_tree and delete_if_exists anywhere,
and oslo.utils provides same methods in module fileutils. We can use
them from oslo.utils if we need in the futrue.

TrivialFix

Change-Id: I280b674dca3738d26c2bed2cf71e94775b370cd5

commit_message:
Add link to new guide in old install guide

Additionally, reworded redirect instructions on the old page and removed
the "work in progress" tag from the new installation guide.

Change-Id: I0c5e4d06637627ab19c0c8a63e0056c9691a2cac
Closes-bug: #1612278

commit_message:
[install-guide] Import "Flavor creation"

Import "Flavor creation" under a new "Create Compute flavors for use
with the Bare Metal service" block inside of the "Integration
with other OpenStack services" section.

Change-Id: Ic37f43a34d577f99d9a1f08300a87c553c1b026f
Partial-bug: #1612278

commit_message:
[install-guide] Import "Image requirements"

Import Image requirements under a new "Creating and adding images to the
Image service" block in the "Configure integration with other OpenStack
components" section.

Change-Id: I503f8c60c7579e7ae5daf30032eb0b047ad40531
Partial-bug: #1612278

commit_message:
[install-guide] Import "integration with other OpenStack components"

The following sections of the legacy install guide were imported:

  * Configure Compute to use the Bare Metal service
  * Configure Networking to communicate with the bare metal server
  * Configure Tenant Networks
  * Configure the Bare Metal service for cleaning

Change-Id: I5cf832401aba9499e9eec9bd50adcbedd356cb00
Partial-bug: #1612278

commit_message:
[install-guide] Import Install and configure sections

The following sections of the legacy install guide were imported:

  * Install and configure prerequisites
  * Install the Bare Metal service
  * Configure the Bare Metal service

Only changes made to the documentation are the following:

  * Formatting changes (code-block, proper lists, etc.)
  * Structure changes (installation and configuration are now under a
    single section)
  * Heading titles formatting [0]

[0] http://docs.openstack.org/contributor-guide/rst-conv/titles.html

Change-Id: I0f1f5dacd4ed31ccfb4ac38c1ff2ecfc94e99ca4
Partial-bug: #1612278

commit_message:
[install-guide] Import "Bare Metal service overview"

Import service overview in the new install-guide and provide a link in
the old guide that points to it.

Additionally, Swift was added to the list of interactions and Cinder was
removed since it is not yet available.

Change-Id: Ica6a9aae2c35f293228ffb75b2cf82478eb568a5
Partial-bug: #1612278

Fix Newton approved specs list

Missig the spec title of live-migrate-rescued-instances.rst
breaks Newton approved specs list in the following page.
So fix it.

http://specs.openstack.org/openstack/nova-specs/specs/newton/index.html

TrivialFix

commit_message:
Backported hacking version update to stable/liberty

The version of hacking in test-requrements.txt was beyoind
the stated in global requerements. Cinder, nova, neutron,
glance are using the hacking version according to global
requrements and with this patch manila alligns rows.

Updated the version of hacking and fixed severel pep8 issues
due to the hacking version propagation.

Cherry-picked from https://review.openstack.org/262781/

Change-Id: Iefdf48725e5f3664a29166c44223d149e23cf84e

feature provided in Nova.

Seria console access is enabled using a new config flag; this flag
plus the required base_url for the nova-serialproxy are also passed

'}]
commit_message:
Add support for serial console proxy access

Support access to instances via optionally enabled serial console
feature provided in Nova.

Seria console access is enabled using a new config flag; this flag
plus the required base_url for the nova-serialproxy are also passed
over the cloud-compute relation for use in nova-compute units.

This is only supported in OpenStack Juno or later, and replaces
the standard output to the nova console-log.

Change-Id: I3bfcca88bd6147be337e6d770db7348170b914e6

commit_message:
Use SSHClient to manipulate bridges on remote hosts (libvirt driver)

As a temporary solution, requires '~/.ssh/id_rsa' file for
connect to the remote host without using password.

- For initializing the SSHClient, will be used the same parameters
  that are used in the 'connection_string' for libvirt driver:
  qemu+ssh://<username>@<host>:<port>/system
- <username> is optional, will be used the current user login
  as default;
- <port> is optional, will be used 22 as default;

Change-Id: Iee79761929c811769d9cffb0668f7c5216f27e33

[{'created': '2016-09-26 04:33:32.000000000', 'message': 'Using sys.exit(main()) instead of main()

TrivialFix: Similar [1] in Kolla project
As we known, Exceptions are raised by the sys.exit() function. When they
are not handled, no stack traceback is printed in the Python interpreter.
Therefore, when using sys.exit(main()) instead of main()
may be more readable and reasonable.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/349353/

Change-Id: Icf5e8a4718dd66d070b0ddc5749a8a0d1abb72c2
'}]
commit_message:
Using sys.exit(main()) instead of main()

TrivialFix: Similar [1] in Kolla project
As we known, Exceptions are raised by the sys.exit() function. When they
are not handled, no stack traceback is printed in the Python interpreter.
Therefore, when using sys.exit(main()) instead of main()
may be more readable and reasonable.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/349353/

Change-Id: Icf5e8a4718dd66d070b0ddc5749a8a0d1abb72c2

instackenv.json.j2. After that, i'm getting json errors in
"openstack baremetal import --json instackenv.json":

Expecting property name: line 35 column 1 (char 7322)

This patch remove an extra comma which makes instackenv.json
file non-valid syntax.

Change-Id: Ic80cc57f30747679147da4f11a8f34e206b00662
'}]
commit_message:
Fix instackenv.json template

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/375490/ did some cleanups in
instackenv.json.j2. After that, i'm getting json errors in
"openstack baremetal import --json instackenv.json":

Expecting property name: line 35 column 1 (char 7322)

This patch remove an extra comma which makes instackenv.json
file non-valid syntax.

commit_message:
Change the default Fuel's Keystone token expiration

The amount of time a token remains valid should be decreased to
reduce potential security risks. This commit changes the defaults
to 6 hours. Also, this commit contains some styling cleanups.

Change-Id: I8563f89a1165d1f423ef59a86fab0f95a8444a25
Closes-Bug: #1585130
(cherry picked from commit 0f2304fdff1bc12c096e0db3497b0fc8833488b2)

commit_message:
Add update puppet-lint to check puppet-tripleo manifests

After fixing upgrading the current version
of puppet-lint (1.0.0) and some prv. nits
we can start using the latest version of
this package.

These gems were removed as they depends on puppet-lint 1.0.0

  #gem 'puppet-lint-absolute_template_path',   :require => 'false'
  #gem 'puppet-lint-trailing_newline-check',   :require => 'false'
  #gem 'puppet-lint-variable_contains_upcase', :require => 'false'
  #gem 'puppet-lint-numericvariable',          :require => 'false'

Change-Id: I71f7ddbf9dd0f54ac5f438476017b6ec89c5ca36

commit_message:
Fix test_apps_pagination test failed

Murano now add the 'Application Development Library' in devstack,
this lead test_apps_pagination test failed.
This patch remove it from packages_list.

Closes-Bug: #1627971
Change-Id: I6450d629080407c83402a55b814e10de4bd3f567

commit_message:
failed to stop freezer-scheduler

The SystemExit exception should be raised by calling sys.exit() in the
funtion freezer_scheduler.stop(). And the statement
self.scheduler.shutdown(wait=False) should be used only for no-daemon
mode(CTRL+C).

For daemon mode, if the statement
self.scheduler.shutdown(wait=False) is used, it will raise another
exception "SchedulerNotRunningError". The daemon will exit after
10 seconds.

Change-Id: Ia0a0075bf7429071e02996c6f2aa2e8e13ffd4e6
Closes-Bug: #1627018

commit_message:
Add Python 3.5 classifier and venv

Now that there is a passing gate job, we can claim support for
Python 3.5 in the classifier. This patch also adds the convenience
py35 venv.

Change-Id: I3950d4cceffeffb7bd4b950c854d7088b706814a

Looks good to me. Please proceed with invalidated tokens.'}, {'account_id': 21970, 'date': '2016-09-27 11:49:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Thanks for the update but I think this is not the right way to approach this issue. I'd rather the caching was turned off completely and we discussed all use cases and limitations before enabling again.

This modification currently addresses only the user-collision but the credential expiration is similarly prohibiting and we are working on additional stuff (that has been in the pipeline forever) that is also affected by the caching.

So I would ask you to disable caching completely for now. Maybe implement a config option to intentionally turn it on in case there are places where it is really needed."}, {'account_id': 8731, 'date': '2016-09-27 12:04:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Dougal, what do you think?

I would say: if we know how to quickly fix a problem with exprired tokens we can do it now w/o disabling caching. If it requires some serious research then I agree with Andras.'}, {'account_id': 9712, 'date': '2016-09-27 12:10:01.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Add the User ID to the cache key

Without the user ID users could potentially access clients created for
different users. For example, if an admin user caused a client to be
cached a standard user would have escalated privileges until the cache
was invalidated.

Partial-Bug: #1627689
Change-Id: Id5d54b4d9f854ff1f1ebd659550362a4f6ca4558

commit_message:
Add client caching for OpenStack actions

This change adds caching for all the actions. When an action request
is made, the cache is checked to see if a client has already been
created. If an existing client is found, the keystone token expiration
is verified to still be current within the configurable window. Once a
client's token becomes invalid a new client is created and the cache
is refreshed.

The new configuration option for setting the token expiration window
is expiration_token_duration present in the default section.

Change-Id: I854f0251d9ec3623700d8a4025df8f1bc632a3e9

commit_message:
Use --config-file from oslo instead of --config

Switch freezer-agent to oslo config file parsing.

--config is breaking the typing of int values.
Oslo.config is smarter about typing.

Change-Id: Iee048ebe9e2ac3074e28494176d8d74b7c6045d3

commit_message:
Change default value of elasticsearch replicas

After executing "freezer-scheduler register" we face problem that
all shards failed in elasticsearch (ES).

If we use number of replicas "0" according to ES documentation
for one node installation then this issue disappeared.

After "first use" of freezer tool cloud engineer can add
additional ES nodes to cluster and fine tune this value
in configuration file.

Change-Id: I4f2a6562358aefb6244f8d0590a9f138db19a925

commit_message:
Use assertEqual() instead of assertDictEqual()

In unittesttools, assertDictEqual() and assertEqual()
are implemented by using '!=' operator. But assertEqual()
can handle dict, list, set and so on. So we just call
assertEqual() to make the tests simpler.

Change-Id: I051ce0a96ab0883fdb907ca24bce7e47580758d1

commit_message:
Fix variable for replicator config options

The config_options should be a variable and not a string, this was an
oversight in the move to simplify the replication configuration options.

Change-Id: I2e914ef4acee02442e9e44e180290a7346f256a7

commit_message:
Fix the url of Cinder endpoints

When use "openstack endpoint list" to list the endpoints of
cinder service, the url is not right. This patch fix it.

closes-Bug: #1627061

Change-Id: I43756421680f4ce59f7cbfb02509aa96c9e5ca9b

commit_message:
Properly cleanup listener on simulator exit

Calling server's wait() after stop() is required.

Change-Id: I16b6ead9c1c63abe2a90296637bb0672fc74083e
Closes-Bug: #1584743

commit_message:
[zmq] Implement round-robin/fanout in the driver

* Implemented ZmqSocketScheduler
    - Which does fonout/r-r
    - Creates separate sockets for different
      connections (discards zmq r-r feature)

Such approach makes it possible to get more control
over socket connection. Using this approach we can
implement heartbeats and acks the same way for
direct connections and with proxy.

This also makes possible to impelement fanout in
a correct way for direct connections.

Change-Id: Id1471acd9940cbf61b40536dc61a098bead67ced
Closes-Bug: #1606272

commit_message:
Update certificate creation for urllib3

urllib3 1.18 was released today and contains new more correct hostname
matching that takes into account the ipAddress portion of a certificate
and disallows matching an IP Address against a DNS hostname.

Change-Id: I37d247b68911dc85f55adec6a7952ed321c1b1d8
